title: angry_german_kid
body:
The "Angry German Kid" is the main character in a viral video, depicting a young teen having a violent temper tantrum when things don't go his way in a video game.

In reality, the video was staged, and was intended by its creator (the teen who plays the Angry German Kid) as a parody of what many people feared, that violent video games would lead to gamers being violent.  It is one of a series of videos made by the teen, who parodies other societal phenomena such as the "gangster".  However, when the video was played on German TV, the TV producers lied and told the audience that this was an unstaged incident, secretly taped by the boy's father.

title: red-crowned_crane
body:
Latin: [i]Grus japonensis[/i]
JP: ã‚¿ãƒ³ãƒãƒ§ã‚¦ãƒ…ãƒ« ([i]tanchou-dzuru[/i])

A rare, endangered East Asian [[crane (animal)|]] species, distinctive for the red patch on its head which is actually bare, brightly-colored skin. This plus the black neck, white streak leading from the red crown partially down the neck, and white body make them easy to identify. This crane is one of the largest crane species.

Overall, they are snow white with black secondary flight feathers (in flight, these are the row of largest feathers present on the "lower arm" of the wing). This can appear like a fluffy black tail when the birds are standing, but the real tail feathers as well as the primary flight feathers are actually white. The bill is olive green to greenish horn, the legs are slate to grayish black.

Males are black on the cheeks, throat, and neck, while females are pearly gray in these spots. 

Some artistic renditions may show a black tail or black primary flight feathers if the artist did not reference a photo or accurate illustration of the bird in flight. Regardless, if the crane has a red forehead or a line delineating this marking, it is almost certainly a red-crowned crane.

In Taoism this crane is a symbol of longevity and immortality. It also symbolizes luck and fidelity.

title: image_comics
body: Image Comics is an American comic book publisher and is the third largest comic book and graphic novel publisher in the industry in both unit and market share. It was founded in 1992 by several high-profile illustrators as a venue for creator-owned properties, in which comics creators could publish material of their own creation without giving up the copyrights to those properties. Its output was originally dominated by superhero and fantasy series from the studios of the founding Image partners, but now includes comics in many genres by numerous independent creators. Its best-known publications include [[Spawn (comic)|]], Savage Dragon, [[Witchblade]], [[The Walking Dead]], [[Invincible (series)|]], Saga, Jupiter's Legacy, and [[Kick-Ass]]. This publisher founded by Founders Erik Larsen, Jim Lee, Rob Liefeld, Todd McFarlane, Whilce Portacio, Marc Silvestri, & Jim Valentino.

title: yakisoba_spill
body:
When a character accidentally spills their [[yakisoba]] while draining it.

This is strongly related to a brand of [[cup ramen|cup]] [[instant soba|soba]], "Pe'young Sauce [[yakisoba]]" sold by Maruka Shokuhin. Its reputed nostalgia-evoking flavor has remained unchanged since its introduction in 1975. However, for many years, the container was unfortunately not sufficiently improved, leading to countless accidents in which the noodles spill out while draining the hot water. If you have ever heard a Japanese person say their preparation of yakisoba went wrong, it's more than likely that this product was the culprit, or products of a similar vein. Since then, they finally adopted a more modern type of lid for some of their product lineup that is also used by other brands of yakisoba, where the lid has a dedicated corner that can be peeled to reveal slits that allow only the water to pass through.

title: kusazuri
body:
Kusazuri (è‰æ‘º) are the plated armor skirt commonly seen on traditional Japanese samurai armor, attached at the bottom portion of the [[dou]], the chest armor.  They are composed of a grid of small plates ([i]lamÃ©s[/i]) made from laminated leather or iron and riveted together in a fashion similar to [i][[sode]][/i] shoulder guards.

Their role is to protect the waist and upper thighs while still giving flexibility, much like their Western equivalent, [[faulds]] and tassets.  

A related piece of armor is the [[haidate]], a set of similarly-constructed thigh guards worn underneath the [i]kusazuri[/i] but affixed directly to the thighs instead of swinging freely.

The simple cloth equivalents found on kendo [i][[bougu]][/i] training armor are called [i]tare[/i].

title: bayberry
body:
Waxberry (Morella rubra Lour.), a evergreen tree species in the Myricaceae family, has a neat, spherical crown; its branches are fragile and easily breakable. The leaves are leathery, alternate, lanceolate or ovate in shape; the plants are dioecious or occasionally monoecious. Female flowers are in soft racemes, bright red and thread-like; the fruit is a spherical drupe with nipple-like protrusions on the outer surface, coming in red, purple, white, pink, and other colors. The flowering season is in April, and the fruiting season is from June to July.

Waxberry is native to Sanqi Market, Yao City, Ningbo City, Zhejiang Province, China. The Shiao Site has the earliest and most accurate remains of the waxberry tree in China, dating back to 2520 BC, which is over 4500 years ago.

title: conte_di_cavour_nuovo_(kancolle)
body:
The second remodel of [[Conte di Cavour (kancolle)|]] from [[Kantai Collection]], released at the same time as her debut in the Kancolle 2021 Summer Event in August 2021.

The main difference between the base form and the remodel is that the remodel's dress doesn't have sleeves.

This is a hypothetical remodel based on plans to modernize her following heavy damage incurred in the Battle of Taranto that went unfinished at the time of the Armistice of Cassibile in September 1943. The superfiring 320 mm turrets were to have carried two-step platforms for additional AA weapons (work was already done by summer 1943); the 120 mm turrets, while not removed, were to have been modified to receive the new 135 mm dual purpose twin mounts, and an additional Gufo radar installed on the foremast.

The second and third remodels of [[Kantai Collection]]'s [[Kongou (kancolle)|]].

For her second remodeling, this new form revamps her costume and rig and modifies her hairband (the "wings" are now [[radar]]s, the band itself is now fully gold/brass instead of a gold/brass and black pattern). This is the most obvious change if she is not depicted with her rigging as her [[nontraditional miko]] outfit remains unchanged. 

More than 5 years later, she obtained her third remodel, termed Kai Ni C (or Hei). This form revamps her costume and rig further and takes advantage of Konishi's art style evolution as well as given cues from other Konishi ships. The most notable features are her boots (similar to the Shoukaku-class Kai Ni), her headband (more intricate), her jacket (now collared) and sleeves (back to being attached to her top) as well as her rig (more detailed for the HD/HTML5 era and features some [[torpedo tubes]]).

[spoiler]The CPUs find that the only way to defeat the revived Deity of Sin [[Magiquone]]/Arfoire is to use [[gehaburn|an evil sword]] which grows in power when it kills one of CPU lineage. [[Noire (neptunia)|]], [[uni (neptunia)|Uni]], [[Blanc (neptunia)|]], [[rom (neptunia)|Rom]], [[ram (neptunia)|Ram]], [[Vert (neptunia)|]] and [[neptune (neptunia)|Neptune]] all reluctantly sacrifice their own lives so [[Nepgear]] can use the sword and save Gamindustri. She defeats Magiquone/Arfoire, but the latter taunts her that a world with only one CPU - without strife, without contest - will eventually stagnate and rot, and when that happens, she will return.[/spoiler]

The remake, Hyperdimension Neptunia Re;Birth 2: Sisters Generation features an alternate "good" version called the Holy Sword Ending, which splits from the Conquest Ending partway through and leads to a [[good end]].

Leo Minor (the [[cub|Lesser]] [[Lion]]) is a small [[constellation]] located in the Northern celestial hemisphere. Its brightest star is Praecipua.

Leo Minor usually represents 3-4 connected stars, with two main ("body") lines forming an obtuse angle, sometimes with a third straight line added. In some cases, a fifth star is added below the "body", making it a quadrilateral. The constellation lies directly above its "parent" [[Leo (constellation)|]] (the Lion) and below [[Ursa Major (constellation)|]] (the Great Bear).

title: transformers:_generation_1
body:
[quote][i]"ROBOTS IN DISGUISE...!!!"[/i] - Official slogan.[/quote]

The original 1984 [[Transformers]] toyline and cartoon series, retroactively referred to as Generation 1 (or G1) after the Generation 2 toyline's release. The series consists of 4 TV seasons with a theatrical film set at the midpoint, as well as two companion comic runs by [[Marvel]] - one produced in the US, and the other in the UK. 

The G1 TV cartoon is notable because it was made in an 80s [[mecha]] anime style. The [[box art]] for the [[toy]]s based on the cartoon was made by [[Jeffrey Mangiat]]. For art done in his style see [[Jeffrey Mangiat (style)]]. The [[Marvel]] [[comic]]s company also contributed to the original franchise by developing the whole fictional Generation 1 universe of the TV series and its robot characters info and backgrounds, all created by Marvel comics writer "Bob Budiansky":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bob_Budiansky. 

The [b]Transformers: Generation 1[/b] tag is for the original series and supplementary media only. In [[Japan]], the G1 continuity lasted much longer and encompassed several non-G1 series in its framework; on Danbooru G1 follows the original G1 continuity, so the several direct sequels G1 received that are exclusive to Japan are not covered under this tag. For those series see the following tags:

title: wild_arms_1
body:
The first game in the [[Wild Arms]] series, encompassing both the original PS1 release and its remake Wild Arms: Alter Code F.

Taking place in the fantasy world of Filgaia, Wild Arms follows the adventures of a band of miscreants and adventurers called Dream Chasers who scour the world in search of excitement and fortune. The player assumes control of a young boy named Rudy who has the ability to operate powerful weapons called Ancient Relic Machines (ARMs), forbidden remnants of a lost age that resemble guns. Along with his companions Jack and Cecilia, the group must use their respective skills to navigate through the vast wastelands and dungeons of Filgaia and prevent an otherworldly threat from reviving their lost leader and destroying the world. -- Wikipedia

The PS1 Wild Arms started the series' recurring idea of steampunk, spaghetti western-styled worlds and characters blended together with typical fantasy world ideas like magic and summonable deities. In addition, both Wild Arms games are lauded for their storylines and characterization.

The PS1 version only has three playable characters:

* [[Rody Roughnight]]
* [[Jack Van Burace]]
* [[Cecilia Lynne Adelhyde]]

The PS2 version adds four new PCs who were all present in the original as NPCs.

title: evolutionary_line
body:
A post centered around evolutionary lines of [[Pokemon]] and similar franchises ([[Digimon]], etc).

Also applies to [[fakemon]] or [[original]] [[creature]]s/[[monster]]s, so long as it's clear that they're part of the same evolutionary family.

A few notes:
* For this tag to apply, the picture should reasonably be about evolutionary lines. That is, the theme connecting characters in the picture should be the fact that they're part of the same family, not that they're part of the same franchise.
** For example, post #4134648 technically contains a lot of evolutionary lines, but realistically nobody searching for this tag wants the majority of posts for unpopular pokemons to be [[everyone]]-style posts.
* For an evolutionary line with 3 or more creatures, not every single one needs to be present. This tag is fine to use if there is focus on, for example, the first stage and third stage of an evolutionary line with the second stage creature not being present.
* For [[Pokemon (creature)|]], Paradox Pokemon (introduced in [[Pokemon SV|Scarlet & Violet]]) are not considered to be part of the same evolutionary line as the Pokemon they are referencing

title: covid-19_test
body:
A COVID-19 Rapid Diagnostic Test, a simple testing device similar to a [[pregnancy test]]. 

They're a lateral flow test used to determine either COVID-19 antigens for a current infection or COVID-19 antibodies for having had a past infection.  The antigen test features marks for C and T, where a single line on the C indicates negative for infection, while a line at both C and T indicates a positive for infection.  The antibody test features the marks C, IgG, and IgM or C, G, and M.  Having a line at the IgG or IgM mark indicates the presence of antibodies and having had a past infection.

h4. External links

* "Wikipedia: COVID-19 testing":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/COVID-19]

title: quick_time_event
body:
In video games, a Quick Time Event (QTE) is a method of context-sensitive gameplay in which the player performs actions on the control device shortly after the appearance of an on-screen prompt. It allows for limited control of the game character during cut scenes or cinematic sequences in the game. Failing these segments, either by failing to take the correct action in time, performing a different action, or taking no action at all takes the scene in a different course/ending.

[b]Susanna Hopkins[/b] (also known as [b]Sue[/b]) is a pretty (but creepy), quiet and very [[petite]] American female [[otaku]] character from [[Genshiken]]. 

She has very long [[blonde hair]] and piercing [[blue eyes]]. Sue loves [[yaoi (object)|]], anime, manga, [[cosplay]] and to follow [[Ogiue Chika]] to everywhere she goes. 

Most of the Japanese phrases Susanna uses are quotes from anime characters. She looks much younger than her real age (which is a mystery) and those who know it (such as [[Ohno Kanako]]) always refuse to tell for reasons unknown.  

In real life Sue's second name is a tribute to Welsh actor [[Anthony Hopkins]], famous for portraying disturbing characters. Her character design was also inspired by [[Izumi Konata]] from [[Lucky Star]].

[spoilers]She ends up with [[Madarame Harunobu]] at the end of the manga series.[/spoilers]

title: little_witch_academia
body:
[b]Little Witch Academia[/b] is a 2013 animated short produced by [i][[Trigger (company)|]][/i] for [i]Anime Mirai 2013[/i]. The short was created and directed by [[Yoshinari You]] and written by Ootsuka Masahiko and was released in theaters on March 2, 2013. [i]Trigger[/i] later began streaming the short with English subtitles on YouTube from April 19, 2013.

On July 5, 2013, Trigger announced at [[Anime Expo]] that a new episode, tentatively titled [i][b]Little Witch Academia 2[/b][/i], would be developed in response to the reception the first episode received. The project will begin production in late 2013 following the airing of [[Kill la Kill]], with a goal to release it for winter 2014. Whilst initially having the funds for a twenty minute episode, Trigger launched a [[Kickstarter]] campaign to extend its runtime by fifteen minutes. The Kickstarter was launched on July 9, 2013 and met its $150,000 goal within five hours. A stretch goal of $500,000 was added to produce a making of documentary and audio commentary for the Bluray release. The Kickstarter raised a total of $625,518. Ootsuka has stated that if the sequel performs well, they may potentially look into producing a television series or full length film. A television series was eventually made for the series in Winter 2017, and was premiered on Netflix.
